<main>
    <section id="locations">
        <h2>Prime Fishing Locations</h2>

        <h3>Eastern Washington</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Potholes Reservoir:</strong> Best for bass and walleye. Spring and fall are ideal seasons.</li>
            <li><strong>Banks Lake:</strong> Known for walleye and smallmouth bass. Spring and early summer are prime times.</li>
            <li><strong>Columbia River:</strong> Famous for Chinook salmon and sturgeon. Best from spring through fall.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Puget Sound</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>North Sound:</strong> Best for Chinook and Coho salmon. Peak season is late summer to fall.</li>
            <li><strong>San Juan Islands:</strong> Known for large King salmon. Best during summer months.</li>
            <li><strong>South Sound:</strong> Great for Coho salmon, best fished in late summer and fall.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Straits of Juan de Fuca</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Straits of Juan de Fuca:</strong> Salmon and halibut fishing is best in spring to early summer.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Neah Bay</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Neah Bay:</strong> Known for salmon and halibut, peak fishing is during summer.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>West Coast</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Westport:</strong> Excellent for salmon fishing in summer. Halibut is also popular.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="gear">
        <h2>Fishing Gear & Tactics</h2>

        <h3>Eastern Washington</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Gear:</strong> Spinning or baitcasting reels, medium-heavy rods, and crankbaits or jigs for bass.</li>
            <li><strong>Tactics:</strong> Cast near structure, such as submerged rocks and fallen trees, for bass.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Puget Sound</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Gear:</strong> Medium to heavy rods, trolling reels, downriggers for deep water fishing.</li>
            <li><strong>Tactics:</strong> Trolling with herring or spoons for salmon, or drifting for bottom fish like lingcod.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Straits of Juan de Fuca</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Gear:</strong> Heavy rods for halibut, trolling reels for salmon.</li>
            <li><strong>Tactics:</strong> Jigging for halibut, trolling for chinook and coho salmon.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>West Coast</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Gear:</strong> Heavy rods and reels, wire line for deeper water fishing.</li>
            <li><strong>Tactics:</strong> Trolling along the coast, using bait or lures for salmon.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="licenses">
        <h2>Fishing Licenses & Resources</h2>

        <h3>Fishing Licenses</h3>
        <p>Fishing licenses are required for all anglers aged 15 and older. These can be purchased online, at local retailers, or at the WDFW office.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Annual License:</strong> Covers fishing for the entire year.</li>
            <li><strong>One-Day License:</strong> Ideal for occasional anglers.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Washington Department of Fish and Wildlife (WDFW)</h3>
        <p>The WDFW manages fishing regulations and resources in Washington state.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Website:</strong> <a href="https://wdfw.wa.gov" target="_blank">wdfw.wa.gov</a></li>
            <li><strong>Contact Information:</strong></li>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Phone:</strong> 360-902-2200</li>
                <li><strong>Email:</strong> <a href="mailto:wdfw@wdfw.wa.gov">wdfw@wdfw.wa.gov</a></li>
            </ul>
        </ul>
    </section>
